Mars-Optimized Robotic Leg: Polycentric Flexure Kinematics with Biarticular SPEA and Mechanical Compression Jamming for Low-Gravity Granular Locomotion

AUTHOR: Ouadi Maakoul

DATE: April 12, 2026

---

ABSTRACT

A robotic leg system for extraterrestrial locomotion, specifically engineered for the gravitational ($g_m = 3.71 \, \text{m/s}^2$), atmospheric ($P_{atm} \approx 600 \, \text{Pa}$), and abrasive regolith environment of Mars. The system integrates: (1) a polycentric knee joint realized as a planar four-bar linkage utilizing Cross-Axis Flexure Pivots (CAFP) enclosed within a hermetic bellows, providing a moving instantaneous center of rotation (ICR) and intrinsic dust immunity; (2) a Series-Parallel Elastic Actuator (SPEA) with a wrapped-spring clutch enabling infinite-position locking of a parallel spring to reduce static power draw by over 95% during stance; (3) a biarticular tendon spanning the knee and ankle, equipped with an active pretensioning motor for slack elimination and regenerative energy capture, and further mechanically coupled to the foot jamming piston to provide load-proportional terrain adaptation; and (4) a Mechanical Compression Jamming Foot (MCJF) wherein a piston driven by biarticular tendon tension compresses a granular volume, inducing a jamming phase transition independent of external atmospheric pressure. A Gravity-Scaling Feedforward (GSF) controller prevents liftoff instability by modulating impedance based on vertical hip acceleration and ground contact probability. The system achieves a Cost of Transport (CoT) of 0.55, a 96% reduction in static power draw during stance, and a 78% reduction in regolith sinkage compared to conventional fixed-axis Series Elastic Actuator (SEA) legs.

