4. ARCHITECTURAL INTEGRATION AND ENERGY SYNERGY

The disclosed leg architecture is designed such that the sub‑systems do not operate in isolation; they form a closed thermodynamic network wherein energy is harvested from one degree of freedom and applied to another. The following table summarizes the integrated functionality and the secondary, often non‑obvious, benefits that arise from the synergistic design.

Sub‑System Primary Function Secondary Synergistic Benefit
Polycentric Knee (CAFP) Shifts ICR to maximize torque at $15^\circ$ flexion. Protects SPEA from impact via geometry; dust‑proof flexures eliminate friction losses and reduce control complexity. Stress-based design ensures fatigue life.
Biarticular Tendon Recycles energy from knee to ankle during push‑off. Powers the Foot Jamming Mechanism (MCJF) and eliminates swing‑phase slack without dedicated sensors.
Mechanical Piston (MCJF) Stabilizes foot in regolith by jamming granular media. Acts as a secondary impact dampener for landing; load‑proportional stiffening adapts to varying terrain compliance.
Wrapped‑Spring Clutch Locks parallel spring for zero‑power stance. Allows infinite‑position locking for smooth adaptation to granular settlement without destabilizing jerks.
Flexure Joints Enable articulation in 0.37 g without friction. Provide 100% dust‑proofing (no sliding seals required), eliminating the primary failure mode of Martian mechanisms.

