6. CLAIMS

What is claimed is:

Claim 1: A robotic leg system for extraterrestrial locomotion in low‑gravity, low‑atmospheric‑pressure environments, comprising:

· a polycentric joint mechanism defined by a planar four‑bar linkage having a moving instantaneous center of rotation (ICR);
· a biarticular tendon element coupling a posterior anchor point of said polycentric joint to an anterior aspect of a distal ankle joint;
· characterized in that said biarticular tendon is coupled to an active pretensioning motor configured to modulate tendon slack and energy storage capacity dynamically across a locomotion cycle.

Claim 2: The system of Claim 1, further comprising a Dust‑Exclusion Housing, wherein all revolute joints of the four‑bar linkage are implemented as Cross‑Axis Flexure Pivots (CAFP) and are encapsulated within a hermetically sealed, flexible bellows system to prevent ingress of electrostatic regolith particles.

Claim 3: The system of Claim 2, wherein the hermetically sealed bellows system is positively pressurized with an inert gas to a pressure exceeding ambient Martian atmospheric pressure, thereby preventing dust ingress and mitigating cold welding of metallic flexure components.

Claim 4: The system of Claim 1, further comprising a Series‑Parallel Elastic Actuator (SPEA) network including:

· a motor;
· a parallel elastic element configured to counterbalance a gravitational load;
· a non‑discrete friction clutch selected from the group consisting of a wrapped‑spring clutch and a magnetorheological brake, said clutch configured to lock said parallel elastic element at any continuous angular position to accommodate irregular terrain geometry without mechanical hunting.

Claim 5: The system of Claim 4, wherein the non‑discrete friction clutch is configured to slip and re‑engage smoothly in response to granular settlement beneath a foot of the robotic leg, thereby maintaining a continuous support force without discrete step changes in joint torque.

Claim 6: A Terrain‑Adaptive Foot for use in near‑vacuum environments, comprising:

· a deformable membrane containing a granular media;
· a Mechanical Compression Piston configured to exert an internal confining pressure on said granular media;
· wherein the transition from a fluid‑like state to a jammed‑solid state is achieved through volumetric reduction of the granular media independent of external atmospheric pressure.

